text:
"me too" (2018)
acrylic and metallic spray paint on canvas.
24x26 (day and night timeÂ view)

i don't normally share the meaning behind my paintings; i want those who see my work to form their own ideas about what it might mean to them. but, as i have myself experienced emotional and physical abuse, i want to say to anyone who might be experiencing abuse that you aren't alone.Â  that even in the darkest days, there's still light. it comes from inside. no one can take that away. see and give credit to your inner beauty. don't hide it on account of others. take all of that pain and anger and deep sadness you might be feeling and let it make you stronger and wiser, let it fuel your fire. shine your light.

text:
happy saturday. i've spent most of my week glued to the tv as i watched the events that unfolded in washington. i like many others was moved by dr. ford's testimony and decided to confide in my husband something that happened to me, that  i've never shared with anyone before. my story was not nearly as traumatizing as dr. fords, but i was still terrified to share it with my husband, whom i trust more than anyone in the world. i can't imagine the strength it took for her to stand up in front of the whole country and share the terrifying event that has haunted her for over 30 years. and now whatever backlash she receives from her bravery will only add to the pain. my only hope for her is that the support she receives is so mighty that the backlash goes unheard and back into mirky shadows it crawled out of.
this is the first time i've ever really talk "politics" on my blog. but this is way beyond politics, what happened this week was raw and very human. millions of people watching her testimony felt it pierce them in the heart because they were reminded of their own terrors or a friend or family members terrors. now that the week is over i see so many ignorant posts from people "attempting" to understand what happened this week and mudding the waters with their misinformation. do yourself a favor, if you haven't watched the testimonies (both), go watch them, educate yourself. if you say you don't have time, then don't post your bullshit, it makes you look dumb. being informed from news clips is not enough. do yourself a favor and educate yourself. we still may have a different of opinion, but at least you can't say you're ignorant ğŸ˜‰
#metoo
.
.
.

text:
gas lighting and sexual assault...
.
yeah iâ€™ve been posting about a heavy topic lately. but i feel it needs to not be bypassed and we need to confront our wounds and bring them into the light.
.
anyways.
.
gaslighting-
.
to manipulate (someone) by psychological means into questioning their own sanity.
.
common tactic of an abusive person that wants to avoid taking responsibility and deflect. itâ€™s easier to try and convince others and even yourself of a lie.
.
gas lighting is dangerous because if someone is successfully gaslit it invalidates what they feel on the inside and it creates a massive amount of a lack of self trust in the victim. they begin to not know what actually is reality.
.
i have had many people try and gaslight me in my life and itâ€™s not something that can happen  very easily at this point in my life. because i trust myself and i back myself up. when self doubt is present gaslighting is able to exploit it.
.
in confronting someone that violated my sexual boundaries as a teenager (i posted about this a few days ago) and when i confronted them on it they completely denied it. they didnâ€™t try and clarify intentions or confusion and possible miscommunications, they just flat out denied the entire experience. which is gaslighting because it was denying factual reality.
.
even though this person denied out of their own self protection...which on one level i understand because most people donâ€™t want to accept responsibility for that kind of thing and take on that amount of shame and pain.(although it doesnâ€™t make it okay) .
even though i didnâ€™t get validated or an apology i feel really good about the fact that i spoke my truth. i feel like i further validated myself and my experience to the other person instead of sweeping it under the rug and pretending like it didnâ€™t happen and that we were cool. iâ€™m all about forgiveness but you kind of have to admit it first before you can be forgiven. anyways, this person knows where i stand and what i felt and what wasnâ€™t okay with me and me owning that truth has an energetic ripple effect in the universe.
(continued in comments)

text:
my final and most important read for #banedbookweek. this is a longâ€™un and continues into the comments below so please keep reading!
ğŸ“šğŸ“šğŸ“šğŸ“š
do you think the people trying to keep this book out of schools realise that, firstly, the surest way to make people painfully curious about anything is to tell them they canâ€™t have it, touch it, read it. young people are resourceful and unless you can monitor them 24/7, if they want to read something, they will?
secondly, that by trying to silence angie thomas, by extension trying to silence starr, all they are doing is legitimising each and every one of the 438 pages of this poignant, heart-breaking, hard hitting, relevant, must-read novel. speaking as a white woman, if youâ€™re reading this as a white person itâ€™s going to make you uncomfortable, itâ€™s going to pose some questions about your own thought processes and itâ€™s going to result in some self-reflection. i hope it is also going to make you angry. i hope that youâ€™re going to cry with starr, come to love her wonderful family unit and that from this point onwards think critically about media reports and the absolute legitimacy of the #blacklivesmatter movement.
ğŸ“šğŸ“šğŸ“š
i wish we were past the point where #blacklivesmatter is met with a flood of #alllivesmatter or #metoo is met with #notallmen. these defensive, knee jerk reactions are designed with the sole purpose of derailing all important  conversations and silencing voices that need and deserve to be heard. the fact that children are having to receive instruction on how to interact with police officers as a matter of survival makes me feel physically sick. 
the same victim-blaming rhetoric is aimed at victims of police brutality as victims of sexual assault, â€œsure, he was unarmed and shot in the back but he dealt drugsâ€ strikes an unpleasantly familiar pose to â€œsure, she was sexually assaulted but she was drunk.â€ (similarly, â€œhe has an outstanding police record and heâ€™s such a loving fatherâ€ sounds a lot like â€œhe has such a bright future, heâ€™s so good at sports, he has female friendsâ€) the message here, loud and clear, â€œthey had it coming.â€
(cont. in comments ğŸ”½)

text: hello everybody! iâ€™m so honored to take over @_weareher â€˜s instagram account today. itâ€™s an extremely special day for me, not just because i get to talk about recovery from abuse but also because i get to celebrate a year alcohol-free today! a quick synopsis of my history: my father sexually abused me for years when i was between the ages of 3-6. starting when i was 13 i began battling a mood disorder and had my first depressive episode when i tried to take my own life. throughout eighth grade, high school, college, and a few years after, i bounced from abusive relationship to abusive relationship. i hated myself and the men in my life fed off that and used it against me. i have been diagnosed with c-ptsd, bipolar 1 disorder, and bulimia nervosa. in 2015 i was raped by a stranger at a â€œfriendsgivingâ€ party, and even though i told the cops, it was a month later and with no physical evidence they said i had no case. on september 29, 2017 i made the decision to quit drinking because i had gotten into a bad cycle of drinking to get rid of my thoughts and feelings- it gave me an ulcer, and i had to quit. a year later, i have to say itâ€™s the best thing i ever did for myself. i cut out all toxins (and toxic people) from my life. it has taken tons of sweat and tears to make it through this year (and this life) and come out on top, but with the love and support of my fiancÃ©, my mother, and my therapist it has been possible. i hope my story can help someone who may be struggling with any form of abuse or addiction, as addiction often follows abuse since the survivor is looking for a way to escape reality. it is possible to overcome abuse, and it is possible to lead a â€œnormalâ€ happy life after trauma. it takes a lot of hard work, but the rewards are endless. #weareher

text:
#metoo 
i have spent so long, believing that my story isnâ€™t worth telling.  that the details donâ€™t matter, that all the perpetrators have been forgiven.  yet, there is an aspect of sexual misconduct and abuse that doesnâ€™t go away for the recipient.  it is transformed throughout our lives, oft times with the help of a beloved, and ultimately we become better people, better partners.  however, the act of â€œreceivingâ€ can become riddled with shame.  this means, that survivors of sexual abuse have to untangle a deep web of conflicting emotions that make it nearly impossible to feel safe in love and physical intimacy â€” until the healing is complete.  yet, the healing is never complete.  so, to the male patriarchy and the media that is too blind to see, i say f*ck you, your time is done.  the old way is dying.  the new way is here, and itâ€™s going to wipe your slate clean.

text:
every woman & queer i know is exhausted. exhausted and angry and worn out. and yet, miraculously, fighting harder than ever to burn this patriarchy to the ground. thatâ€™s called courage. to be terrorized daily by a culture that prioritizes white, wealthy male safety above all else and continue tearing that culture down brick by brick.

last night during a live self-care tarot session with @ravishly, i pulled some cards for anyone feeling lost in their fear and the rage it brings them. the spread i used is one that i created when i was stuck in my own cyclone of triggered memories of abuse. when the present slams the past around inside my heart, this is the spread i turn to. it clarifies my fear so i can embrace it with courage and use it to shape the change i want to see in this world. 
card 1 || where is the fear? || 3 of swords. this fear is so painful â€” an old wound. this fear is our individual experience of a collective trauma that all survivors of patriarchy carry with them. 
card 2 || what wound feeds this fear? || 10 of swords reversed. wound-ception. the legacy of patriarchy lives in our bodies. the fear weâ€™ve been subjected to is trapped in us along with our motherâ€™s â€” and her motherâ€™s, and hers and hers.... and all of ours. and weâ€™re. fucking. done. being. stabbed. our wounds are our weapons, and we will use them to liberate ourselves.

card 3 || what shadow does this fear illuminate? || knight of cups. we are witnessing the contents of our hearts. we see the three swords piercing it more clearly than ever. we give words to these wounds. we say #metoo.

card 4 || what do i see in the unknown? || 7 of coins. we are growing a revolution planted long ago. harvest is on the horizon.

card 5 || what does the unknown see in me? || the sun. we are the light bringers. abusers can no longer hurt us and hide us in shadow. we are light. we are fire. we are, to quote the great empress ariana grande, â€œcoming to give back everything the darkness stole.â€ the unknown knows that #timesup, and itâ€™s ready for us to meet it in the future.

so, this is why i have complex post-traumatic stress disorder. i donâ€™t particularly like being called a â€˜survivorâ€™ - i only use that word because itâ€™s a better word than â€˜victimâ€™, and that doesnâ€™t feel right either. ptsd from sexual trauma can have life changing symptoms. it makes everyday life very hard. what was once a normal task, becomes something that seems impossible to do. it can effect your relationship with others, especially those you want to be intimate with. i struggled with being touched for a very long time. every time i thought i was brave enough, my brain told me i was in danger. do you know how angry this makes me? i should not of had these experiences taken away from me. â¡ï¸ itâ€™s taken a while for me to get where i am now. iâ€™m in a healthy relationship where i am treated with the kindness and respect i have always wanted for myself. i count myself as lucky to have found someone as amazing as my boyfriend. but i had to love myself first. i had to understand on my own that i was worth so much more than what i had previously been given. ğŸŒ· to the survivors: i believe you. i hope you have the courage to speak up and to keep on flourishing. you deserve so much love, and one day, you will receive it. keep going. ğŸŒ·

text:
i'm really affected by the posts i've been seeing lately where people are asking why survivors of sexual violence don't come forward. 
how often have you admitted to something as simple as falling over yourself? don't you wish no one saw that happened? imagine that but a situation colossally worse. imagine feeling like your entire life has come to this point and you've nowhere to go from here. it takes incredible courage to do what christine ford has done. 
this post goes out to every brave woman or man who's faced an ordeal and survived. 
#metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford #believesurvivors #poetsofig

text:
there are myriad ways to feel small in this world.
â€¢ 
prepping for my final nols course of the season has brought two very dissonant senses of â€œsmallnessâ€ to the forefront of my mind. i have been listening to the ford testimony and experiencing feelings of loss, defenselessness and hopelessness. meanwhile, weâ€™ve been discussing wilderness: a place where i feel strong in my smallness (though american wilderness ideals are not without their problems, too). the last six months have been a period of immense growth and emotional reckoning for me. and iâ€™ve spent a lot of time mulling over these topics. so, how do we change our cultural narrative?
a few of my thoughts: more honesty, more consent, more intimacy, more education, more intentional parenting, more sharing stories, more affirmation, more compassionate asking and listening... â€¢
i want to have these conversations: tell me your story, iâ€™ll tell you mine. iâ€™m headed back in to canyon country, so snail mail me until october 18 (or use technology) and iâ€™ll write you back:

vernal, ut 84078 â€¢

text:
{warning: description of rape}
it was a sober sunday afternoon in a dorm room, and we were affectionately spooning on a beanbag chair, watching tv. i had met him the week before at a small get together after a friend introduced us. we had flirted all night, eventually exchanging numbers, and texted all week, until he invited me over. we talked about world issues, our exes, our childhoods and our dreams as we cuddled, half tuned into the tv. i remember smiling about how nice it felt to emotionally connect with someone. then i felt his cold hands yank down my jeans from behind in one swift motion. he pinned me to the ground and started thrusting himself inside of me sharply. my mind raced and froze all at once, but no thought would stick long enough to translate to an action. my body lay motionless, other than the jolt of his weight jerking me. i begged my legs to move, i begged words to come out of my mouth, but shock paralyzed me. i was starting to regain control of my functions when his roommate suddenly walked in. we made eye contact and a tear rolled down my face. i shoved him off of me, and ran towards the door, swooping my purse up on my way out. i ran all the way to my car, where i cried, screamed, and silently cursed my body for failing me. i was 18.
.
i flashed back to when i was 14, and was sexually assaulted for the first time. i didnâ€™t know then, that it would happen yet again when i was 23.
.
each incident combined, makes up no more than an hour of my life. but their presence in my mind has never diminished. i could never wash off all the pain iâ€™ve carried all these years. i can never bypass the feeling of violation and betrayal from these boys and men that i knew, who each stole a piece of my dignity and robbed me of my rights.
.
after watching the kavanaugh hearing, i felt compelled to tell my story in solidarity with dr. ford and every other survivor of sexual assault and rape. i needed to speak my truth for those who canâ€™t, and those who need to borrow some strength to heal. you are not alone. we are strong. and we get to write the rest of our stories.
.
now please, pick up your phones and call your senator to tell them to vote no on kavanaugh!

text:
augusta ada king, countess of lovelace (10 december 1815 â€“ 27 november 1852) was an english mathematician and writer, chiefly known for her work on charles babbage's proposed mechanical general-purpose computer, the analytical engine.
she was the first to recognise that the machine had applications beyond pure calculation, and published the first algorithm intended to be carried out by such a machine.
as a result, she is sometimes regarded as the first to recognise the full potential of a "computing machine" and the first computer programmer.
her educational and social exploits brought her into contact with scientists such as andrew crosse, sir david brewster, charles wheatstone, michael faraday and the author charles dickens, which she used to further her education.
ada described her approach as "poetical science" and herself as an "analyst (& metaphysician)".
her mindset of "poetical science" led her to ask questions about the analytical engine (as shown in her notes) examining how individuals and society relate to technology as a collaborative tool.

augusta ada king, countess of lovelace (10 december 1815 â€“ 27 november 1852) was an english mathematician and writer, chiefly known for her work on charles babbage's proposed mechanical general-purpose computer, the analytical engine.
she was the first to recognise that the machine had applications beyond pure calculation, and published the first algorithm intended to be carried out by such a machine.
as a result, she is sometimes regarded as the first to recognise the full potential of a "computing machine" and the first computer programmer.
her educational and social exploits brought her into contact with scientists such as andrew crosse, sir david brewster, charles wheatstone, michael faraday and the author charles dickens, which she used to fuher her education.
ada described her approach as "poetical science" and herself as an "analyst (& metaphysician)".
her mindset of "poetical science" led her to ask questions about the analytical engine (as shown in her notes) examining how individuals and society relate to technology as a collaborative tool.

text:
iâ€™m aiza and this is not my story.these are a bunch of events that i will never let anyone describe as my story because to be honest girls out there including me donâ€™t need a label of being a â€˜victimâ€™ of harassment or bullying.
the first time a man in a market intentionally bumped into me,i was humiliated.but instead of getting comforted at that time i was told that this is why i should cover my whole body properly.so i did,i started wearing knee-length shirts.a little time later i got into a new school,apparently they didnâ€™t believe in uniforms because of every kidâ€™s individual personality but they did have a dress code,specifically for girls.the dress code included compulsory hijab(so much in the name of individuality lol).
so being a new student i wanted to make as much friends as possible but clearly i was unaware of some other rules of the school.the rules included that girls canâ€™t be friends with boys even though it was a co-ed school. i thought it was absurd because it was but what i did not think was that the boys at this school were not capable of being friends with.they were all friendly with me but behind my back i was the â€˜hotâ€™ topic.that how iâ€™m a slut for being friends with so many guys and wearing a bit of western and how my shirt was once see through.and this isnâ€™t it,i got to hear sexual jokes which made me uncomfortable.later when i got to know all this and realized that being friends with them was a bad idea,they started associating me with almost every guy i was friends with, talked about my body parts and called me names.
i believe that verbal harassment is equal to physical because it is what it is.it really disturbed me and i also tried to confess it to a teacher but she said its better to keep quiet. 
i donâ€™t blame the boys who did this with me and a few more girls as much as i blame their parents,this school and our society.i put this blame on the parents,school and society because its always the girls who are told to not get â€˜too friendlyâ€™ ,to cover properly or not to go out alone.when the boys should be brought up properly and taught how to respect a girl the way she is and that itâ€™s okay to get rejected. #metoo

text:
all too often, women are not heard. they are not believed. their story does not matter. this happened to me when i tried to share my own experience with this type of predatory behavior. i was ridiculed, shouted at, accused of lying, called names and ostracized.Â it's easy to condemn a stranger on your tv screen. it's harder to accept that someone you've shared thanksgiving dinner with could be capable of such behavior. as disappointing as that experience was and continues to be for me, it's encouraging to see the emergence of the #metoo movement and see so many women finding their voices, telling their story and receiving support and justice.

typically, abusers display a mentality of superiority and certainty; they go right on the attack to exalt themselves whereas in contrast, a real victim is most often confused and uncertain. abusers also go into extreme victim mode. they look for an experience but not a relationship & therefore often forget the incident; they experience excitement in fantasizing and in the exhibitionism. these individuals are often extremely intelligent, charismatic, and talented. even people who know them well cannot conceive that they are even capable of exploiting others sexually. such predators are masters of deceit. and their most striking quality - they blame their behavior on others. i will never forget. i will never stop telling what happened. the truth will never change.

text:
wow, just when you think you can move on and be healed and live a life among sane, kind, compassionate individuals, your government letâ€™s you down. 
we survivors of sexual assault (and there are millions of us) are getting triggered from every direction. 
what this means: 
the memories of our attack come flying back, as we witness another be brave enough to share her story. her story is my story, is our story. 
the violation is relived as we watch the alleged  perpetrator respond with such hostile and righteous damnation. what about her rights, my rights, our rights? weâ€™re pissed off too! his attempt to use his power to power over, is our experience all over again. 
we feel the deep betrayal from our brethren as a large portion of our our government sides with the alleged perpetrator. their actions, their response, their lack of compassion for us is harmful, mean, demeaning and could set devastating standards for years to come if they vote in favor. 
i didnâ€™t want to write this book or share my story, but i had too. i heard a voice that said, â€œit is time.â€ i followed the guidance, not knowing the why. i know now. the writing process helped heal me even more. i know now, in the deepest portions of my being, that it can help heal you too. this book was written for you, for us. it is a story of divine empowerment. it will not only help to heal your internal wounds, it will raise your spirit and when women are one with their power, there is nothing they canâ€™t do, like help heal this world. 
this is no longer a #metoo movement, this is a #wetoo movement. it is time! 
#iknownow #awomanshealing #violencetovictory #traumatotruth

text:
i remember being 18 and registering to vote. i refused to associate with either democrats or republicans as my party, because of the immense hypocrisy i saw on both sides. there was no #metoo movement at the time, but i saw several credible women, with compelling evidence against bill clinton, being silenced - and i was horrified to know that more than half of american woman voted a rapist to the highest office of our country (twice). you may say times have changed, but i don't believe that. we had just as much information, evidence, and credible witnesses then, as we could have ever needed to convict him of his crimes.

the next level of hypocrisy - brett kavanaugh is accused of sexual misconduct in high school. there is no credible evidence, no correlation of stories, and the friend named by christine blasey ford refutes her story, as well as everyone else named. yes, she has a right to be heard - the same right clinton's accusers were never given). but, if we want a fair and just system, we must hear both sides before making a decision. listening to npr today, i was angry at how many people listened to her testimony and not his defense. college classes played her testimony in class.... without the defence. how can we be just without allowing both sides? how can we teach justice?

i was sympathetic hearing ford's testimony, and i was moved by emotion. i felt i knew the truth. but after hearing kavanaugh's defence, i felt i knew a different truth. i don't deny that ford was the victim of abuse. i don't believe that abuse was at the hands of brett kavanaugh. perhaps i'm wrong.

yet, my opinion doesn't matter in the court of law - it shouldn't matter. what matters is a just decision based on evidence and testimony, not emotion and opinion.

text:
the #metoo movement, and most recently the events of the last few days, has forced me to grapple with my own past and future â€” iâ€™m sure pretty much everyone here feels me. iâ€™ve often found myself wondering what might happen if the man who sexually assaulted me resurfaced years from now. what if he became a noteworthy person? â—½

words often fail me in these moments, but i still felt strongly compelled to add my voice to the multitude of those outraged by this kavanaugh circus masquerading as justice. yesterday i created and recorded a performance with @midgraycollective to highlight the incredible lengths survivors must go to in an attempt to have their stories heard and believed â€” though we know it is likely our labors exist only in vain. â—½

i have created performances in the past, but this piece comes from a place of vulnerability unlike any before. these are some stills from the performance, and i would also love if you visited @midgraycollective to read the artist statement and view an abbreviated version of the full 9 minute video. there is a 1 minute clip currently in our feed, and a 2 minute series featured under the â€œafter all this timeâ€ story highlight.

#ibelieveher

text:
what does being empowered look and feel like to you? one of my favorite things to do is to work with women through what they perceive as traumatic significant emotional events in their lives; often this is regarding sexual abuse and helping them feel empowered, connected and see more truth than they ever thought possible. 
i want to offer a slightly different perspective based on my own healing s. 
i feel most inspired to share, because by allowing women to believe they are in any way a victim, we disempower all women.

i've come to realize that itâ€™s actually repression, not freedom, to speak out and consider yourself a victim. empowerment is standing up and having the courage to know that you can create anything you want for yourself regardless of your circumstances. iâ€™m not making the behavior right or justifying it or saying someone belongs in a certain job or not. i do believe the most empowering thing we can do when we really hear someoneâ€™s pain is to stay neutral and not get caught up in their story. to notice and clear our side where we have emotional triggers is the best way to serve. 
we canâ€™t heal anything we judge so thereâ€™s sooo much opportunity right now to open our hearts and stretch a little further to have compassion for these women while holding a belief that we are all here for an empowered purpose. remember, everything happens for a reason. as hard as itâ€™s been for me to believe this one at times, and yes, i too have had dozens of â€œme tooâ€ moments and experiences but i also want to and do choose to stay in charge of my life and choices. that doesnâ€™t mean itâ€™s always easy. 
now iâ€™m in no way blaming or saying we as women invite these experiences or have done anything wrong. i do believe we are always given opportunities that allow us to grow. 
3 things that helped me to stay out of the victim mentality and helped me realize what was really most important to me: 
1. reminding myself this too shall pass and thereâ€™s nothing iâ€™m going through i canâ€™t handle. ğŸ™

2. belief if i let this run my life and hold onto it, iâ€™ll never create the life and relationship i really want. ğŸ“

3. we always attract the support we need at the right times. ğŸ’“

text:
#whyididntreport #metoo because i was a child. because i was afraid. because i knew my mom would be heartbroken. because i was ashamed. because i wasn't ready to share my story...because i'm still not ready to share my story. 
i am very good at making people believe every thing is fine...hell i even believe that smile. (me at 16)

i keep seeing people saying where's the proof? we don't need proof to tell our truth. if i did choose to tell my truth, i have no proof but that doesn't mean it didn't happen. that doesn't mean i don't struggle every single day to keep breathing to keep a smile plastered on my face. our traumas are ours to tell whenever we feel we are ready to tell them.

i keep seeing people saying where is the proof? we do not need proof to tell our truth. if i did choose to tell my truth, i have no proof but that does not mean it didn't happen. that does not mean i do not struggle every single day to keep breathing to keep a smile plastered on my face. our traumas are ours to tell whenever we feel we are ready to tell them.

text:
as she speaks today,
she speaks of 
how they made her go all numb,
and she settled for
staying just mum.
but , 
regrets of
those silences 
now linger somewhere
&
shriek within her,
s t i l l.
-
why are we not ever taught of not ignoring, speaking- looking back and reacting? 
why can't we gather courage to look back unto bloody lustful eyes that only speak of condemn?
why do we all shiver, hesitate?
why are we the ones feeling ashamed of ourselves?
why do we avoid and not react?
why do our voices echo within ourselves?
are we the ones letting them?
so many more simple questions in simpler words- the answer is one : ...for it's just the way it is.
right?

#waysoftheworld

we @bossladycollective__ 
stand with the dr. it's time to stop blaming and shaming women.
- 
then saying stupid stuff like why didn't she say something sooner, in her case she did. look how she is being treated in 2018 just imagine what she would have endured 30 years ago. 
_
think about this if you are a woman you have probably been sexually assaulted or harassed in some way or you absolutely have a family member. friend or co-worker that you know has been.
_
 if you are a man the same goes for you even if you do not know it tte women in your life have been victimized. it could be your mother, sister, wife, daughter, co-worker any woman you know. 
_
we challenge every man to gently ask 5-10 women you are close to if they have been victimized and watch. if she says no watch her demeanor pay attention to her body language. remember women have been conditioned to marginalize sexual abuse or worse to blame themselves.
_
if she says yes let her know that all men are not like that and just listen. don't try to fix it or make it better you can't. but you can listen. be her advocate and help her find resources to heal..
_
if you are a woman in need of help please dm us or call your local crisis center. 
_

text:
the past few days i've had to exit the news cycle to take care of myself. dr. ford's experience was so sadly similar to mine, at a party, in college, with friends i thought i could trust. ....
listening to her have to sit in front of a panel of 90% white men and describe one of the deepest darkest moments of her life.... and then be asked how much she had to drink that day.... ....
but i woke up this morning with a realization. 
brett kavanaugh is scared. republicans are scared. white men all over the world are scared. ....
brett kavanaugh threw a tantrum at his testimony as he realized that - suddenly - his actions have consequences. the way he treats people, fucking matters. that people will listen to a woman, even if they don't believe her yet. they will listen. he is afraid. ....
they are calling for an investigation because they are afraid. 
they see the power that we have to vote, to influence, to tell our stories, and they are afraid. ...
they are afraid of our power.
... and maybe, right now, that is enough to make change, however small. ...
maybe they don't believe us, but they will listen and call us 'credible' which is progress. ....
but most importantly, they are afraid of our power, so they lash out in anger. 
#pussypower #metoo #mybodymychoice #ibelivedrford #believewomen #cancelkavanaugh #fucktrump

text: i generally try to keep this arena of my life a light and fluffy (pun intended) one, but just a quick comment in regard to so much of what has been happening. being a woman is still not a fair and equal thing in this world. it doesnâ€™t matter how strong, confident, smart, or capable you are. it doesnâ€™t matter where in the world you live, how old you are, what color skin you have, or whether you were even born one or not. we watch the news and weâ€™re not shocked, not even horrified. weâ€™re sad, hopeful, angry, frustrated, and frankly full of triggered memories of our own experiences. this is simply and unfortunately how the world has always been for us, and yes itâ€™s great that conversations are happening and abusers are being called out but people need to realize that this isnâ€™t new. this isnâ€™t rare. we all know that guy, we all have a story if not a few. as a woman that travels often by herself both for work and play, iâ€™m always conscious of the extra risk iâ€™m naturally at. friends constantly text me to see where i am and to tell me to be safe. i have to learn routes before i leave my hotel so i wonâ€™t be seen checking my map constantly, figure out where i can or canâ€™t go at certain hours of the day, pretend to have fake phone conversations sometimes, watch everything served to me like a hawk, never wear headphones while walking around to stay aware. itâ€™s a very real and constant game beyond â€œletâ€™s try not to get robbedâ€ of â€œletâ€™s try not to get rapedâ€ that most men simply donâ€™t have to even consider yet is so ingrained in us that somehow we can genuinely still enjoy ourselves while it all just operates innately in the background. it sounds and honestly is depressing as fuck but whatever happens, iâ€™m proud and happy to hear the voices getting louder and see new eyes opening even if itâ€™s only a few at a time.  big or small, every story counts. i swear iâ€™m having a great time in barcelona ğŸ˜… but also if i donâ€™t post in another 12 hrs, this was my last known location ğŸ˜€ğŸ‘ğŸ¼ğŸ“ğŸ™†ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ (jk not really, because you also canâ€™t post your live location because- creeps ğŸ˜’)

text:
of all the cards in the isis tarot deck, this one came to me while the calcified edifice of shadow masculine fought for its life on prime-time television.
.
as so many women in my life and across the planet continue to process and re-process trauma in real-time as this trial continues, please know that you are not alone. .
please know that you have allies and witnesses everywhere. please know that as the feminine continues her struggle to reclaim the throne from which she was wrongfully cast, the masculine is rising right beside you.
.
know that these moments mark the shifting of the paradigm, and the impetus for mature masculine, divine masculine, to return in force to this world through the hearts and bodies of good men everywhere.
.
i know it might not seem like it. particularly right now. but i promise you, the unmistakable cry from the feminine is calling the masculine back to consciousness, back to integrity, back to honor, back to trust. it may take time, but there many working to make that change now.
.  thank you for showing us how. thank you for braving the seemingly immutable vestiges of corruption, inequality, and systemic abuse. thank you for teaching us how to meet you in this.
.  tell us what you need.
teach us how to hold space for you. 
keep showing us how to be better men.  we are listening.  we are with you. .  #kavanaughhearings, #metoo, #menforwomen, #divinefeminine, #divinemasculine, #nomeansno, #him4her, #osirisrises, #isistarot

text:
tw sexual assault/rape --------------------------------------------------- i started getting sexually assaulted and harassed at 13 years old. by my senior year in high school i lost count of how many times it had happened. i had been raped. by college harassment was expected. by college i believed my body wasnt mine anymore. a few years had passed since my rape and i was terrified to say it. my first year, i shared my story. after, so many friends told me theirs. thanking me for my words, my vunerability. years after, my body is mine again. i am mine again. if you believe dr. ford is wrong, unfollow me. unfriend me. i believe her. so many of our stories are eerily similar to hers. and i'm tired of us not being heard or believed. you don't believe her, unfollow me.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
. .

text:
i usually stay out of any and all political talk, but recent events have sparked a strength and courage inside me that iâ€™ve never felt. a feeling that iâ€™m finally ready to share my story as much as i feel i can today. if you canâ€™t show compassion or support, stop reading now and keep scrolling. let me preface by saying iâ€™ve never publicly shared any of this or written it out so please bear with me.

nearly 20 years ago between the ages of 10 and 11, i was sexually abused. it happened many, many times over several months. i never told anyone during that time. i never reported it. i felt ashamed, confused, alone, terrified and dirty. i felt like it was my fault. i was a child. i didnâ€™t understand. i was violated to my core in the deepest, darkest way over and over again. i suppressed it completely for years. 
even though nearly 20 years have passed, i still struggle to find the words to remotely express what happened to me. how it changed me forever. how i still suffer from ptsd associated with this abuse. how some days i donâ€™t want to be touched. how some days all i want is to be safely held. how certain things trigger me when they â€œshouldnâ€™tâ€. how it caused me to struggle in relationships and still does. how i feel overwhelmed with emotion at times and donâ€™t know how to deal with it. 
even though i didnâ€™t report it, it still happened to me. no one should be chastised for not speaking up sooner. no one should be called names or torn down for speaking up when they feel they finally have the courage to do so. society feels like they should have a say in how you handle your story and they donâ€™t. i stand with all those who were abused, whether they reported it or not. i believe them. i see them. i hear them. they have inspired me to share my story so that maybe i can inspire others to find the strength to speak up & out in the way that works for them. so that i can create more healing for myself. so that i can learn to let go of the trauma that sometimes engulfs me. that i can find peace with it. i believe in myself. i am a survivor. so are you. speaking your truth is the most powerful thing you can do in this life. ğŸ’“ #metoo #realshit #truth #believewomen #standup

text: this week was difficult for me, as iâ€™m sure it was for many of you. i am tired, sad, & angry. dr. fordâ€™s testimony was credible. her responses were consistent. she provided expert testimony on basic memory functions. she shared this account several times many years before kavanaugh was nominated. she had no motive to share this & every motive to keep it to herself yet felt it was her duty to tell her story. kavanaugh, on the other hand, has every motive to lie. many who knew him said he deceived the senate judiciary committee & lied under oath. that alone is disqualifying. while ford was able to explain from a neurological perspective why her memory is reliable, kavanaugh simply claims he is, miraculously, the first person to remember every detail of every event that happened every time he was inebriated. that is implausible, especially when paired with descriptions of his behavior by college classmates. itâ€™s possible he doesnâ€™t remember the incident, because he was too drunk or because it was insignificant to him. ford, on the other hand, convinced me this incident was one she will never forget, both because of her memory function & because it permanently altered her life. many are saying he is innocent until proven guilty, & there is not enough evidence to convict him beyond a reasonable doubt. yes, in a criminal trial where liberty is at stake, we apply these high burdens. this is not a criminal trial. his liberty is not at stake. what is at stake is a lifetime appointment to the highest court in the land to which he is not entitled and for which many others are qualified. credible allegations of serious crimes must be disqualifying. also disqualifying is that he made no effort to hide his irretrievable bias & partisan animus. the point of the supreme court is to be a neutral, nonpartisan arbiter. kavanaughâ€™s unhinged rant against democrats & his threats of reprisal clearly show he has no intention of being fair-minded & nonpartisan. this is disqualifying. he does not belong on the supreme court. if your senator is undecided, please call them & ask them to vote no. this is too important, both for the integrity of the court & the future of survivors.

text:
i usually stay out of any and all political talk, but recent events have sparked a strength and courage inside me that iâ€™ve never felt. a feeling that iâ€™m finally ready to share my story as much as i feel i can today. if you canâ€™t show compassion or support, stop reading now and keep scrolling. let me preface by saying iâ€™ve never publicly shared any of this or written it out so please bear with me.

nearly 20 years ago between the ages of 10 and 11, i was sexually abused. it happened many, many times over several months. i never told anyone during that time. i never reported it. i felt ashamed, confused, alone, terrified and dirty. i felt like it was my fault. i was a child. i didnâ€™t understand. i was violated to my core in the deepest, darkest way over and over again. i suppressed it completely for years. 
even though nearly 20 years have passed, i still struggle to find the words to remotely express what happened to me. how it changed me forever. how i still suffer from ptsd associated with this abuse. how some days i donâ€™t want to be touched. how some days all i want is to be safely held. how certain things trigger me when they â€œshouldnâ€™tâ€. how it caused me to struggle in relationships and still does. how i feel overwhelmed with emotion at times and donâ€™t know how to deal with it. 
even though i didnâ€™t report it, it still happened to me. no one should be chastised for not speaking up sooner. no one should be called names or torn down for speaking up when they feel they finally have the courage to do so. society feels like they should have a say in how you handle your story and they donâ€™t. i stand with all those who were abused, whether they reported it or not. i believe them. i see them. i hear them. they have inspired me to share my story so that maybe i can inspire others to find the strength to speak up & out in the way that works for them. so that i can create more healing for myself. so that i can learn to let go of the trauma that sometimes engulfs me. that i can find peace with it. i believe in myself. i am a survivor. so are you. speaking your truth is the most powerful thing you can do in this life. spreading love & light forever ğŸ’›ğŸŒŸğŸ’›

text: i lay here, wondering what i can do that will change the world. we cant keep ignoring the facts; the world has been dying & there are those who wish for its destruction so they ascend/transform/move on to an afterlife, not considering that this is their only life. greed drives their actions, if not hatred & zeolotry. they poison the earth when we have the ability to save it because they refuse to adapt to change. they scream at those they deem less than, because they need to feel superior. they use force to push those around them into line, or worse into submission. the scars they leave & the bruises that swell are then blamed on the victims, because it was their fault for not just letting them do as they wish. they excuse themselves, saying that they will be rewarded for the faith. my faith died, so long ago, and i have lived with so much hurt inside that i stopped trusting everyone. ive cultivated my mind & my life to pursue truly one thing; to lead the rest of my life with happiness, laughter & love. to those whom have shared your #metoo & #whyididntreport , i understand your pain, ive shared my story & #ibelieveher . kavanaugh is a shining example of partisan elitism that doesn't care about normal everyday folks. call your representatives,  post on their pages, tweet like your rights are on the line. because they are. #weareannamaniacs #gaygeek #dragisfamily #dragislove #youarenotalone

text:
meet @sarah_e_olson, hereâ€™s her reason why #myreasonwhy: â€œmy very very dear friends and their wonderful company astra labs have created a campaign ( #myreasonwhy ) to show the positive sides of mental health, the reasons why people continue to push through all the tough situations in life. my reason is simple - i want to be there for people struggling with mental health, even if i am not. i want to be a person who only brings joy into other peoples lives and i want to make those around me feel safe and happy and most importantly, loved when they're with me.Â i wish to be nothing but a little ray of sunshine in other people's lives - brightening their day and making them happy whenever they're feeling down. the only power i have right now is words. please listen to them. read them again if you have to. i love and care about you so much, even if weâ€™ll never meet. and i refuse to let anything happen to you.
there will be so many reasons to smile if you stay - think about it...dogs, cuddling friends, laughter, sunsets, puppies, new music, bubble wrap, soft blankets, oceans, travel, meeting new people and being accepted for who you are, when someone you don't know smiles at you really nicely, compliments, books, fall, art museums, watching your friends grow to be beautiful successful people, when someone says "this made me think of you", memes, sunshine, pretty flowers, freshly made bread, waking up early and realizing you still have hours to sleep, going outside when it's cold and watching your breathe show up in the cold air, visiting places you've never been, meeting internet friends for the first time (and second, and third, and fourth), dancing and singing to some musical (that is way out of your range but c'mon who really cares?), checking things off of a to-do list, a good workout, smelling spices or food in the air when someone's cooking - i could go on and on and on. most of all though, the thing that makes life great are the people i've surrounded myself with. i love you guys with all my heart.â€

-

so yeah, we are going to talk about it.

text:
#boymom
itâ€™s not just a trendy saying for t shirts or a hashtag to describe days filled with messes and rambunctious mayhem.  #boymom is a huge part of my identity.  it describes the fact that two pieces of my heart beat outside of my body.  my boys are my joy and it is my honor to raise them to be men of character.  it is this reason that the current cultural climate deeply disturbs me. 
as a woman i used the #metoo hashtag with a feeling of solidarity.  i refrained from details but i used the hashtag because i too have been groped, intimidated, stalked and sexually harassed more times than i can count.  iâ€™ve sat and cried with friends whoâ€™ve been raped and sexually abused, iâ€™ve commiserated with women who have been blamed for the impropriety and lack of self control of the men around them and iâ€™ve chewed out the cat caller for describing my body in shameful ways.  i, as a woman of almost 30,  am not naive to the problem of sexual misconduct our society is plagued with and am determined to teach my boys to be true gentlemen that respect and value women as fellow image bearers of god. 
unfortunately, i also will have to teach them that a woman can destroy not only their reputations but their livelihoods with a mere accusation, simply because they were born male.  my boys are growing up in a society that favors the â€œoppressedâ€ and teaches them that simply being white and male colors them in shades of evil.  they will be judged on their gender, race, and assumed privilege far before their character and integrity are considered.  my boys will live with the reality that a simple accusation of debase and heinous acts can destroy their lives, and if they defend themselves they are in danger of being categorized as â€œdangerousâ€, â€œa threatâ€ or a â€œbullyâ€. the society my boys are growing up in is not one of justice but one of corruption.  itâ€™s a society where vulnerable women are manipulated for political gain, where a wife and daughters are discarded as collateral damage and the constitutional mandate of â€œinnocent until proven guiltyâ€ is  applied only when it suits a particular power narrative. **continued in comments**

text:
there are infinite reasons why a survivor doesn't report.

text: for my children and anyone who is willing to be receptive to this...strength is relative. to the extent which we are able to offer and accept this sense of relativity is up to each of us individually to adopt and adapt to. in regards to the #metoo movement and coming from a mother who is raising boys who â€œwill be boysâ€ because it is my job to wield these humans as they offer their personalities...i demand respectâ€”as a woman and as a human being. when something seems inappropriate to me i let my boys know. inappropriate language. inappropriate touching. inappropriate behavior. i let them know. not passively. aggressively. forcefully. outspokenly. i am raising men. i want them to be respectful men. i want them to understand the world but i can only teach them about the world that we exist in. i will teach them to be kind and i will reprimand them when i see them acting out of entitlement. i will not shame them for who they are. i will not teach them that they are to fear growing up in this world as men. i will believe â€œherâ€. the royal â€œher.â€ sadly i have come to understand that stories are based on perspective and sometimes...people lie. so, what am i to do with that? i am a female and i am friends with females and sometimes our story is not even the truth. truth is not an illusion. truth is what happened. accountability is often not taught. so, i will move forward offering as true of a perspective as i am able to. that is really all that i can do. i am trying my best to pass this same skill on to my boys. i will shame them for what they should shameful for but as a woman raising two men in this world, i am here for them as well as i am here for myself. logan and dylanâ€”iâ€™ve got your backs and there is nothing about growing up as men that you should be afraid of. this world has too many other obstacles that you are up against. i am your support. i love you. parentsâ€”your jobs are a lot more than materialism and â€œgoodâ€ behavior. i hope we all have this understanding.

listening with bated breath.
.
.
as the trial of brett kavanaugh and dr. christine blasey ford has been presented to the senate judiciary committee and in turn the public, so many are tuned in. hearing dr. fordâ€™s testimony yesterday, iâ€™m embarrassed to admit that the first thought that i had was, â€œis that so bad?â€ followed by, â€œisnâ€™t that behavior normal?â€ to which afterward, i was forced to look at the behaviors iâ€™ve heard of and experienced in my life. while i have never experienced what dr. ford has, i was reminded of an experience i had in high school that terrified me and that i never addressed out of fear and judgement. i was walking through the football field on my way home when i saw one of the members of the team, also a man who happen to have a locker next to mine, sitting on the bleachers. he called me over and i went even though we rarely spoke. as i approached he said, â€œgive me a blowjob.â€ my eyes widened as i realized the situation i was in. i was 13 he was a senior and 6â€™5â€. i immediately turned around and started walking away and he shouted, â€œyou little bitch!! get back here!â€ i started running and he chased me. it was terrifying. i got off the school property and turned just to see that he had stopped the chase. i ran home trembling with fear, wondering, â€œdoes he know where i live? will he find me?â€ .
.
. 
this happened early in the school year and i had to go through the rest of the year, sharing a locker next to this man in silent fear. i never told anyone. i hope that because of dr. ford and anita hill before her, that women and girls will learn to speak up, be heard and believed. this behavior is not ok even if some of us have, through silence, thought it was. .
.
.
be the storm. â›ˆ

text:
we need to speak up about the difficult and uncomfortable things going on in our lives and in the world. this requires vulnerability. having a safe space to openly express ourselves is a great way to set the stage for finding our voice.  i recognize, however, that even if we whole heartedly believe in something fear may still find a way to block us from expressing our truth. .
this fear is obvious in the women who are now finding the courage to share their stories. i also had an experience recently which really highlighted this. i read a post sharing the tragically horrific story of a rohingya refugee @natgeo . i felt so much compassion, empathy, and sadness reading her story that i felt inspired to post a small comment expressing my empathy, recognition, and awareness for the tragedy that is occurring. yet, when i went to the comments section i stopped. there were so many disrespectful and aggressive attacks against culture, religion, race.....that i was scared to post. scared of what, iâ€™m not sure. being attacked myself, saying the wrong thing, having my words misread and twisted. it made me realize that likely so many of us actually care, despite hiding ourselves, and so many of us have kindness and compassion in our hearts, yet we keep silent. we need to create safe opportunities for open, non-judgmental dialogue so we can begin to open up and understand one another. we need to be able to ask about things we donâ€™t understand without fear of being bullied as that kid in class who asked the stupid question.  it is through curiosity and respectful communication that we will start to change our perceptions of one another. if you have a thought, question, interest in anything at all, iâ€™m not saying i have the answers, but i am willing to do everything in my capacity to create a judgment free space to discuss and expand our awareness of one another. .
.
intrinsicpsychology@gmail.com
.
.

text:
no question itâ€™s been an emotionally charged week in our country. i was debating if i wanted to post about the current political climate...seeing that i usually avoid political debates....but i realized by listening and talking with sooooo many of my friends who have personally experienced sexual assault, that this isnâ€™t a political conversation at all....but an ethical and human respect topic. .
no matter what the outcome on the political front (which as hard as it is to accept...i canâ€™t currently control) the fact remains that our country is broken when it comes to how we handle these issues. itâ€™s true that we canâ€™t change the past, but by addressing these testimonies in the present, i believe we have the potential to reshape the future. to teach our youth about boundaries, repect and consequences, and hope that these conversations going forward will result in immediate response and recourse, rather than shame and ridicule. 
#hopeforthefuture #timeforachange #ibelieveher #metoo

text: this week, i missed the classroom. i missed the children who play grown in the hallways and sneak in at lunch to hold hands and divulge secrets, in need of safe space. i missed channeling my concern and ache for the world and its people into lessons. i believe that our work as educators is to illuminate the interconnected nature of human existence, and to lay bare the missteps of our stories, and to cultivate hope in young people so that they know with a burning certainty that they are worthy, capable beings who have the power to truly change the world. i missed the classroom this week. and yet.. she, too, plays grown in the world. she, too, comes back to me to press our hearts together and tell truths. she, too, will be an instrument of divine purpose. she, too, can change the world. how glorious to lean into motherhood in these times, and to find my breath in order to tell my girl of all the glory within her. thereâ€™s healing in that, too.

text:
when women support each other,  there is nothing we cannot do. 
___
___

this year has been filled with hard questions, deep dark exploration of my past, my experiences, my psyche.  there have definitely been some moments over the past year that i have doubted everything and everyone and more importantly - i doubted myself. i have explored my feelings around past sexual assaults and the use of power to sexualize me in almost every job i have ever had.  i have remembered things from my past that have made me cry uncontrollably.  many things i stuffed way down in my psyche from years past are being aired and it's hard - but it's also necessary. 
___
___

to all of you strong and amazing women who have shared your stories... thank you.  to all of you goddesses who have experienced this... i believe you,  i support you,  and i stand with you. you are not alone and we are all together.  we will no longer be ignored. 
___
___

we are breaking free of all that bound us to the past, to the darkness, to the silence.  we are stronger, brighter, better and we will rise higher than imaginable. ğŸ’–
___
___

text:
for a few weeks now, i had been booked to do another pop culture panel on @cbcthenational last night -- but at the last minute, producers decided to switch gears and invited me to do a segment with rosemary barton and julie lalonde on #metoo, public discourse around sexual violence, and dr. ford/brett kavanaugh.

it's still such an infuriating, draining, emotional time - but i still try to hold onto hope that we won't see a similar anita hill/dr. ford moment in another 27 years. 
swipe through to catch a clip of a point i made around what this week tells us about believing survivors -- and see the link to the full segment in my bio!

#ibelieveanitahill 
#ibelievechristineblaseyford
#believesurvivors

text:
we've heard from so many of you that are struggling with the news surrounding the supreme court hearings. in response, @mwachicago reached to two mental health experts to present at free online webinar today, saturday, september 29th.

join rukhsana iqbal, md and shannon mccray, lpc for this important forum on "coping with #metoo" from 10:30 am to 12 pm. submit your anonymous questions beforehand via bit.ly/discussionqs

all are welcome from any background, any walk of life. now more than ever, we need to stand together no registration required. to join this online.webinar, please visit:

bit.ly/copingforum

text: i am reminded today how much i am loved by friends and surrounded by healers. i have been blessed with some of the most amazing opportunities to heal from my past trauma. i have shared my story publicly dozens of times and no doubt it has been heard by thousands through tv and radio. i canâ€™t imagine how i would process having to share my story under such difficult circumstances as dr ford did this week. she has courageously made a true sacrifice. i want to live in a world where women do not experience assault so commonly. i want to live in a world where we can report crimes against us without being treated like a lunatic. i want that for americas daughters.  #thankyoudrford #metoo #survivor

text:
it started when i was 8... 2 years younger then my little girl. man after man for 7 years each showing me the evil in the world, each taking a piece of my innocence bit by bit. forever changing my perception of what is acceptable and what love really was. the world was a much different place 20 years ago there were no movements or hashtags for what i went through. no band of women standing united to bring awareness to what was happening to me. so in some way i felt it must have been my fault surely i was doing something to make not 1 not 2 or even 4 men do or say these things to me..... i didn't know... so i held it inside and grew strong. i didn't fully understand the extent of the damage and just how wrong it was until i had a daughter of my own.... a police report does not make one victims story more viable than another... open your eyes â™¡

#whyididntreport #metoo #awareness #rapevictim #strongwomen

text: listening to all the stories on the radio yesterday and reading so many on instagram and facebook, had me sad for everyone thatâ€™s gone through something sexually traumatic. i had to take the time to reflect upon my own past of when i was younger and had little awareness of myself and little regard for how my actions affected others. i have shared fairly openly that i came to the yoga practice because of my shameful past. while i wouldnâ€™t say i have ever sexually assaulted anyone i would certainly say i mistreated others when it came to sexuality. this isnâ€™t easy for me to say out loud. because i am super shameful but the conversations need to be shared openly for everyone to get somewhere on the topic, and i donâ€™t want to stand by and observe people i care about feel isolated and alone. so i am committed to being a part of the solution. i was addicted to the validation i would get from sex. if i was able to get the girl than that would make me worth something to someone, and if i wasnâ€™t than i was worthless. it wasnâ€™t about exerting my power over someone because truthfully i was the one feeling powerless. that being said the perception on the other end may have been different. so i tried really hard to prove to myself that i was worth something in other peopleâ€™s eyes, and it didnâ€™t even occur to me to think about the fact that the girls i was trying to get were likely looking for the same. at around age 24 i woke up. filled with shame and guilt for how i treated girls i isolated myself completely and began studying yoga. i didnâ€™t have sex for about 2 years i believe, and i struggled with allowing myself to be sexual when i finally started dating again. some people i have been able to apologize to, but lost touch with others. if anyone is reading this from my past, i am sorry for who i became, i donâ€™t know what drew me to that place of emptiness and complete lack of self worth, and i am sorry you were pulled into it. my guy friends also endured my unkind, argumentative, righteous behavior, and i have apologized to them, but havenâ€™t necessarily thanked them for sitting me down and having that tough conversation that began my shift. thank you.

text:

text:
the testimony of dr. blasey ford offered a profoundly moving account, in particular the details of what she has experienced in the wake of her revelations.
as she mentions, the worst of her fears have been surpassed.

she has had to move her family out of her home and is living with death threats, email hacking and media hounding, under the constant protection of security guards.

as a society, we perceive this heartbreaking situation as a battle, a fight to be heard. in the fight, there are attackers and victimsâ€”bad guys and good guys.

in the fight, we name a precisely delineated right and wrong where each participant can only be one or the other, and our answer to the â€œwrongâ€ is to accuse, blame, shame, and persecute the persecutorâ€”with the idea that by destroying what we think is dark, we will find safety and an answer to our pain.

within the duality of this fight, there are deep layers of fear and shame.

the shame of a woman who has kept a traumatic secret for decades because of the judgement she feared would be levelled at her, that her response would not be valued or understood.

the shame of a man so childlike in his awareness, so out of control in an alcoholic stupor that he objectified and attacked a fifteen-year-old girl without any concern for the impact of his actions.

the shame of a political party with conservative values rooted in the denial of feminine power, desire, and autonomy.

the drive of a specific political agenda built upon the need to represent this man as a defender of â€œjusticeâ€ within a â€œjustice system,â€ which itself is founded upon blame, shame, judgement, and retribution.. the delight of media and press that canâ€™t get enough of our fascination with sexual shameâ€”more fascinating even than driving by a car accident, or watching youtube videos of people falling and hurting themselves over and over while we laugh.

of course, dr. blasey fordâ€™s testimony must be heard.

of course such attacks must be stopped. any perspective which minimizes the depth of trauma in such situations comes from a place of denial... (cont. in comments)

text:
consent part 4...
parents of teens, what specific conversations have you had with your son or daughter about consent? have you explained that consent or "permission" is required from the other party before they touch them in any way? did you tell them that unwanted contact such as kissing, fondling, grabbing, groping, and penetration is a criminal act of sexual assault? did you tell them that even if both parties consent to intimate contact, the moment one party says "wait, stop, no, hold on, i'm not ready, i changed my mind" then consent has been withdrawn and any further contact can be considered assault? did you tell them that consent is ongoing and they should get a clear "yes" before proceeding to the next stage of intimate contact? did you tell them that drunk, high, and mentally/physically incapacitated partners can't consent; therefore, if you engage them in sexual activity in that state, that is considered sexual assault? did you tell them that just because someone gives consent today, that doesn't mean you don't have to get their permission to be intimate with them tomorrow? if you're not having these conversations, you're not teaching them about consent. and, if you're not teaching them about consent, your child may become guilty of sexual assault. have the conversation!  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
iâ€™m bent! i am woman and i donâ€™t break, i bend!  i first started to bend when i was told that my skinny, dark brown,  adolescent body was not an attribute. i bent further when i was told that i was too outspoken. i continued to bend when i was told that my tears were meaningless and that i must learn to hide them and wipe them away quickly. iâ€™ve been bending. again and again! i doubted my every emotion, thought and action. in this process i became hard. iâ€™m bent because of my conditioning. but iâ€™m not broken. iâ€™m far from it. life keeps bringing it and i tilt, turn, twist and bend to allow it to pass right in front of me.

this has been a heavy week for women. it is sad to live in a world where i am alarmed when i meet someone who hasnâ€™t experienced sexual assault. you know what? itâ€™s been happening since the beginning of humanity. women are only now finding our voices. #togetherwerise. i wrote and published my rape story in 2012 before this movement began. (iâ€™m happy to share the link if you want...itâ€™s not an easy read, tho.) i wrote it because i heard someone else come forward publicly about her own rape and i thought â€œif she could do it, so could i. this might be what i need to do, to heal myself by making it public and reaching other women who have experienced the same pain.â€ and i did. so many people came forward and confided in me about what theyâ€™d experienced. it goes far deeper than the physical act. it took me 8 years to finally begin the process of healing which took another 2 years with therapy, meditation, and a lot of writing. itâ€™s been 4 years since i completed the journey beyond the pain and now i stand, covered in valor oil, with all of the women on this earth - those speaking up, and those unable to. ğŸŒ ğŸŒ

text:
to the woman who spoke up,

my grandmother took 35 years to understand that she wasn't only being "played with" when her uncle visited their house, my boyfriend didn't know that he could be raped at 11, my mother told me to "confirm" things with myself before i complain about the incident that haunted me for years. and all this is exactly why i am not surprised when people ask you "why so late?" people who tell you that you seek attention are the same people who want to replicate hollywood speeches in india but won't hear or know a word in it. 
the same people who would use the #metoo but just won't call out their friends during a casual banter,
the same same people will  encourage women to speak up until it doesn't harm their "wolf pack", the same people who won't understand that when anyone cries or shouts for help, they need some ears and shoulder, not cameras. 
i am not going to applaud you for being strong and brave. i am sad you didn't have a choice. because, apparently, without that, even if you choose to stand on a cliff, be brave, write a blogpost, make 1000 people agree, you won't be able to bring everyone on the same page to validate a harassment which affected a life. 
no, i don't know what happened with you that night, that day, on that road, on full display, in that chat, in that bar, on that stool, in that room, 
but i finally chose to say #metoo along with few thousand women in 2017 here in india and i know how many eons it took us before we stood up with shaky legs and a heavy heart. we can't just leave you or absolutely anyone unheard like that. 
here's us, all ears, all voices, all genders, 
always,

yours, 
survivor,
just like you. - aparna upadhyay ( @aparnaupadhyay )

text:
this has been a hard week for survivors of sexual assault. it has been a sobering reminder for those who have kept their pain in their hearts, of what can happen to them if they come forward, and it has been retraumatizing for those who did come forward and weren't believed. they may feel alone, unheard, and uncared for. the burden of their assault may feel impossibly heavy, and staggeringly isolating right now. so, if you know a survivor, reach out. be present with them for a moment, and allow them to speak. and if you are reading this, and you are a survivor, know that we see you, we believe you, and if you ever need to talk we're just an fb/ig message away. 
image by @emilymcdowell_
#scotustoo #christendomcollege #christendomtoo #metoo

text: i know this past week (month, year) has made a lot of us feel powerless and hopeless. personally iâ€™ve been cycling through a combination of rage, despair, resentment, and sadness. so today iâ€™m trying to spend my energy refocusing on the strength, power, and resilience of women. we are not pawns, or statistics, or defined by our relationships to others (wives, mothers, daughters, etc). we have the ability to shape our collective reality, and weâ€™ve been doing that from the beginning. yesterday maria gallagher and ana maria archila put themselves on the line to stand up for sexual assault survivors, and it made an incredible impact. iâ€™d love to hear from you - who made you proud this week? who was kind to you? who forged the path for others? ps, re: cake message - not all women have pussies, but women do run everything (and fuck the patriarchal noise), thanks for the lyrics @champagnepapi #thesweetfeminist

text: thanks for sharing, i was silent all my childhood life and early adulthood, unfortunately i finally spoke out about my domestic & sexual abuse in 2015. my goal is to continue to bring awareness and encourage girls & women to speak out! #poweroffaith #poweroffaithfoundation @regrann from @theprojectforwomen - hopefully a little humor can break up a dark day... i am trying to wake up from the fog. today and every day forward we reckon that we will no longer sit quietly. we will no longer stand for these type of actions. our bodies, our minds and our hearts will not be broken down by the ultimate fact that most of us will be tormented, harassed, sexually abused and raped in our lives ...or we will spend a lifetime fighting that destiny, guarding ourselves deliberately and forcefully against any of these occurrences. shut us down today and our voices only get louder tomorrow. this is our time, whether you like it or not. #stopkavanaugh @pamela_hanson @theprojectforwomen thank you to #metoo and #christineblaseyford for paving the way. ğŸ™Œ words cannot comprehend or commend you for all that you have done for women on the deepest level.

text:
today's #gratitude in pictures.  #gratitudelist 
i'm extremely grateful for the women who are brave enough to speak up and stand up against their abusers. be it as a young person or 10, 20, 33, 45, 50 or more years after.  thank you for telling the truth.  trauma from mental, physical and sexual abuse lasts a lifetime. we find ways to cope. many turn to self abuse, then go on to abuse others,  but the strong women,  they survive,  they thrive and eventually they are triggered and the truth sets them free. stop #victimshaming #blaming and be accepting of what's going on. #keeptalking #women lift one another up, #bebetternotbitter #metoo #johnmarquez #peterincon #billyoung  #joesantos ... 10, 12, 14, 27 ... it happens,  i've always said their names.  #bravewomen

i was in the price club, and saw "little" jimmy martin, who was also abused by his mom's boyfriend john. i hadn't seen him since that night.  he hugged me and said "i'm so sorry about what john did to you" and all of a sudden it all flooded back to me, i could barely stand up, i went in to shock. as my body heated up, i started to tremble, my knees buckled and the tears came ... my husband didn't know,  neither did the one before him. there i was in that big store having a repressed memory of a horrific abuse and no counselor or hypnotherapy did it, an innocent hello, a hug and an apology from an adult kid who suffered as i did. 
it took years to work through that and the others.  i remember them vividly.  it's why i am the way i am about leaving kids with boyfriends,  friends boyfriends, alone or with other kids/teens, etc. i know what happens,  and i know how long it can take to speak up. i told right away as a child,  but not as a teenager or adult. 
brave women,  keep sharing,  your story, your bravery,  your truth is giving hope and strength to others.  we no longer have to lay back and take it.

i was in the price club, and saw "little" jimmy main, who was also abused by his mom's boyfriend john. i hadn't seen him since that night.  he hugged me and said "i am so sorry about what john did to you" and all of a sudden it all flooded back to me, i could barely stand up, i went in to shock. as my body heated up, i staed to tremble, my knees buckled and the tears came ... my husband didn't know,  neither did the one before him. there i was in that big store having a repressed memory of a horrific abuse and no counselor or hypnotherapy did it, an innocent hello, a hug and an apology from an adult kid who suffered as i did. 
it took years to work through that and the others.  i remember them vividly.  it is why i am the way i am about leaving kids with boyfriends,  friends boyfriends, alone or with other kids/teens, etc. i know what happens,  and i know how long it can take to speak up. i told right away as a child,  but not as a teenager or adult. 
brave women,  keep sharing,  your story, your bravery,  your truth is giving hope and strength to others.  we no longer have to lay back and take it.

text:
i believe her because i walk home at night with my keys or umbrella out just in case.
i believe her because i never leave my drink unattended.
i believe her because i've been in situations where my "no" was not taken seriously.
i believe her because the amount of times i've had men mutter sexual innuendos at me as they pass by or grab my ass in bars is ridiculous.
i believe her because i have too many friends with stories worse than mine.
.
sexual assault is a public health issue. victims of sexual assault are likely to experience anxiety, depression, ptsd, substance abuse, poor self-esteem, and eating disorders. sexual assault can result in sexually transmitted infections and unplanned pregnancies. if pursued to term, an unplanned pregnancy is more likely to experience preeclampsia, poor glucose control, nutritional deficiencies, and as a domino effect of all of the above, poor fetal neurobehavioral development and congenital malformations.
.
on this account, i will talk about all issues that relate to health. please get out and vote this midterm - choose representatives who will stand up for the basic right of female bodies to be respected.
#istandwithsurvivors
