text:
myths about false accusation
myths: â€œlots of women cry rape when they regret sex.â€
â€œwomen accuse celebrities and athletes of rape all the time for money and attention.â€
â€œthe definition of â€˜rapeâ€™ is so loose these days â€“ women can claim anything is rape and get away with it.â€
â€œthey didnâ€™t have enough evidence to prosecute, so she was probably lying.â€
â€œif she was really raped she would have called the police.â€
only about 2% of all rape and related sex charges are determined to be false, theÂ same percentage as for other felonies (fbi). so while they do happen, and they are very problematic when they do, people claim that allegations are false far more frequently than they are and far more frequently than for other crimes.Â  put another way, we are much more likely to disbelieve a woman if she says she was raped than if she says she was robbed, but for no good reason.
on a related note, only about 40% of rapes are ever reported to the police, and this is partly because victims know that if their claim becomes public, their every behavior will be scrutinized, they will be shamed for their sexual history, and they will be labeled as lunatic, psychotic, paranoid, and manipulative.Â  just because someone does not report their crime does not mean it did not happen.Â  furthermore, only one in two claims lead to prosecution, so if the da decides not to prosecute, that says nothing about whether or not it happened. (http://www.rainn.org/get-information/statistics/reporting-rates)
#metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen

when all you want to do is scream until the shingles are lifted,
when your insides feel like flour sifted...
when you want so badly to speak your truth,
and let others know, yeah #metoo

but society would rather walk with a seeing eye dog,
and act more manic than sonic the hedgehog...
overtalk you with their convincing lies,
show more sympathy to the villain and laugh at my cries. 
and you wonder why we've  been silent for over 30 years,
our minds are raped repeatedly by our fears...
justice is not only blind, but deaf and dumb,
the quicker we realize this maybe our country can survive being played like trump.

text:
[trigger warning]this is a photo of me, at age 6. the year my mom introduced me to my stepdad, & me at age 9, the year he started molesting me. i gained weight. my grades plummeted. i cried a lot. a couple of years later, the morning i woke w/semen on my pillowcase, i told my mom, but the pastor told her divorce was not an option. so he kept doing it. when i was 14 my dad found out & my stepdad finally left the house. my momâ€™s church friends told me i had to forgive him (because god) & let my mom move on w/her marriage. my principal pulled me into the office when i was crying in the hall & sternly told me it was time to get over it. 
even as people tell you it isnâ€™t your fault, they tell you to hurry up & move on. get over it. how long will you make this man pay for what he did to you? and we have been taught by our society to stay quiet like good, submissive little girls & take it. 
i call bullshit. #metoo 
p. s. this has been a rough week for us as a nation. be kind to each other today.

text: my post from facebook.....i am feeling compelled to share my story right now. i am done carrying this around with me. maybe just maybe it will help another women with her own voice. i was sexually abused as a child. by more than one person. i am thankful that i don't have a whole lot of clear memories of it. for a very long time as a child i thought i made this up in my head and carried that guilt with me for thinking these thoughts. as i grew older it became apparent that these were things that happened to me. as i hit my teens my self worth was pretty much nothing. i was told that since i wasn't very "smart" i better marry rich or be good at pleasing a man. this is so terribly emotional typing it. i also feel a sense of relief to get it off my chest!!!! i feel compelled to share this to help others that may be going through the same thing. i am raising three amazing children of my own. thankfully i have done everything to protect them from the same stuff i dealt with as a child. i am teaching my daughters to be strong and that their voice matters and their body is theirs! call me a triggered woman acting erratic. damn right i am! i am human, i am a mom, and i am a survivor! i have no ill-will to the people that were involved. i feel sadness that they had to  have had the same thing happen to them. i am so much stronger now than i was back then. i'm done hiding or feeling shame. i did absolutely nothing wrong. honestly i feel that it has giving me the strength that i have today. the universe works in mysterious ways. #metoo

text:
abuse, rape, and sexual assault are rarely clear and easy to understand. 
the stranger hiding in an alleyway who commits one extreme attack and gets sent to jail by the end of the law & order episode is nowhere near the norm. 
crisis counsellors have told me that perpetrators known to the victim are by far the most common perpetrators. 
cops have told me that cases with â€œgrey areasâ€ depending on â€œhe said, she saidâ€ are the most common cases. 
mental health nurses have told me that ongoing traumas intertwined with relationships and other parts of life are the most common traumas. 
this stuff is unlikely to be wrapped up neatly in the stereotypes we see in media and society. 
which is why so many victims struggle to come forward, struggle to report, and struggle with self-blame and guilt. 
if we donâ€™t see ourselves in the â€œstranger in an alleywayâ€ narrative we might get stuck in denial and be unable to access help. 
lots of us suffer a delayed reaction, continuing to love, care for, and remain close to our perpetrators. some of us even initially beg our perpetrators to stay and keep hurting us. the psychology of emotional, physical, and sexual violence is complex and varied. 
even when police explain things to my face, i still feel like everything is my fault. 
so when a woman comes forward to report, society needs to respond in a way that recognises the difficult journey women have almost definitely already been on. 
we donâ€™t need to doubt, interrogate, insult, threaten, or shame victims to test the validity of their claims. itâ€™s not necessary. perpetrators already do that to us. the legal system will most certainly be putting us through that. and most importantly, we will likely be doing it to ourselves. 
when a woman tells you what a man has done, believe her. you literally have nothing to lose. 
#supportsurvivors #domesticviolence #familyviolence #rape #sexualassault #abuse #survivor #ptsd #complexptsd #mentalhealth #believewomen #ibelieveher #metoo #ruok

text: all the emotions this week: rage, fear, shame, hopelessness, defiance, passion, disgust, unity, divisiveness, confusion, exhaustion, helplessness, sadness, compassion. part of me knows that this is a necessary stage of the divine feminine rising: a last gasp of the patriarchy bubbling up to be washed away once and for all. but another part of me wants to - and did - curl in a ball and cry. through mindfulness i bear witness to both these parts of myself: the divine witness, and the human being. for those of you feeling these feelings - and more this week - i see you and i hold you in my heart. for the leaders who are fighting vocally on the front lines- i see you and i honor you. there are millions of us cheering you on. for those on the wrong side of history: i see you and i hold space for your healing as well. #fullplatefullcup #holdspace #mindfulness #honoryourfeelings #divinity #humanity #healing #metoo #believesurvivors #divinefeminine #riseup #grace #faith #selfcare #selflove

text:
#throwbackthursday 
i am not married anymore however my vows of friendship with these 5 women hasnâ€™t faltered, some friendships have span the course of more than 30 yrs..

while the dean of yale law school â€” kavanaughâ€™s alma matter â€” has already joined the american bar association in calling for an fbi investigation into the allegations, harvard has yet to make any such statements.

text: i've spent the week basically on the floor, trying to turn this anguish into song. i write in an attempt to heal myself, my mother, my friends, and my ancestors, all survivors. we have no choice but to keep fighting. to keep speaking up. to keep making art. i refuse to accept that this is the new normal. christine's testimony reminded me that nothing is more powerful than honest vulnerability. she inspired me to continue to live truthfully, because that is the only way. and we will do whatever it takes to continue to #smashthepatriarchy i know that phrase makes some people uncomfortable, and if so, i encourage you to get curious about why. dismantling the patriarchy is not about hurting anyone. it's about deconstructing unsustainable systems that oppress the majority of the humans in the world, and in turn risk us losing the beautiful planet we call home. we need everyone on our side. and until then, we are not going away. we will not be silenced. #believesurvivors #cancelkavanaugh #metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford #ibelieveanitahill #believewomen

text:
both my husband and i suffer from ptsd. mine, from physical and sexual abuse. his, from childhood domestic violence and combat.
.
.
we have endured a great deal of horrifying circumstances. at different periods in our lives, our brains became severly unbalanced trying to cope with what felt like lifetimes of agony.
.
.
alot can be said of our journey, both together and seperate, but i will just leave this here â¬‡ï¸ .
.
love is a verb, like struggle. love is something you do. its not always easy, but its authentic, and real, and so worth it. for those you love, love unconditionally.
.
.
if you are struggling from ptsd, and its umbrella of side effects, (anxiety, insomnia, depression, headaches, confusion, flashbacks, etc)  dont give up! remember you are more than this, more than just one thing. you are not alone. there are tools that can help you, and it gets better. manageable. you can live through this to tell an amazing story of survival
.
.

text:
sexual assault or harassment is more common in women than anyone thinks. it happens to us, every single day. it is ugly, embarrassing and painful - thatâ€™s why no one talks about it.
.
it happens when weâ€™re catcalled on the street, when someone calls us baby or honey, when a stranger puts their arm around us in parties, when a boyfriend tries to convince (force) us into having sex, when weâ€™ve drank too much and they â€œthoughtâ€ we wanted to do it... does any of this sound familiar to you?
.
now that iâ€™m a mom, i cannot bear the thought that june might grow up to experience any of these - because we refuse to talk about it now. our girls need to know how to speak up for themselves.
.
to dr ford, thank you for coming out and telling us the story of what happened to you 36 years ago. your story is as relevant to us now as it was then.
.

text_retweet: my abuser was a teenage boy at my 7th birthday party.  later, when i told my mom, she gave me two choices- did i want him to apologize to me, or did i want to never see him again. i chose the latter.  but as i grew up, and the ghost of that experience followed me into every sexual situation, i began to wish for that apology.  now is your chance, men, if you have a ghost of regret in your past, if you committed assault out of drunkenness or peer pressure or if you were barely more than a child yourself and repeating what was done to youâ€” whatever the circumstances, you can help move the process of hurt towards the healing. you can reach out to her and take responsibility for the trauma you caused. and even if it was 30 years ago, i promise it will still make a difference.  iâ€™m reposting again this great example of what k should have said. itâ€™s a good start.  #metoo

text:
this is not a regular post.

i have so much to say. 
this year i decided to speak out about my #metoo experiences. 
i decided to hang up my fears.

my voice will no longer be buried or drowned out by what i think i should not say or do.

as i forge forward on this path i am grateful my story is not falling upon deaf ears. 
sisters & brothers, if you are going to call anyone or situation out, you better find that bass in your voice and speak the f}*}*k up!! they will try to stop you and discourage your progress, so your feet need to be grounded and stable before you tell them you are not satisfied with this answer, send me up the ladder.

yes, this last situation of sexual harassment on the job happened 3 years ago - but the deep suffering i endure daily is *more* than enough for me to continue to pick up the phone and request to speak with municipal and provincial change makers.

i will be heard.

i *am*being heard, and for that i am grateful.

i will not speak on bill cosby, nor will i speak on the brett kavanaugh case, but i will post this meme and let this simmer in the pot that bubbles over on the back burner. â€œhey america, your racism is showing.â€ #wassatnow?

text: a course in miracles states, â€œwalk, then, in gratitude the way of love.â€ hatred is forgotten when we let go of comparisons and allow gratitude to overcome fear, anger, and sorrow. when we compare ourself to others, what they have and what we do not have, we are creating a separation from the spirit within. the spirit within is where our happiness comes from. our inner light is dimmed when we create a separation that leads us away from love. how can we live a life full of happiness and feel true unconditional love for ourself and others if we are leading with fear of what we donâ€™t have? next time you find yourself scrolling through another social media page wishing you had what another has or looked like they do try this.. stop immediately and bring three things to mind that you are grateful for. the universe will unlock your wildest desires if you could truly appreciate all that you have now. appreciate all you have, ask for what you would like to have knowing you have already been blessed. only then can you surrender your fear and trust that your desires will come at the perfect time.  #acourseinmiracles #gratitude #grateful #spiritual #healing #mindfulness #happiness #selfcare #yoga #study #love #selflove #selfcare #happy #motivation #motivationalquotes #happymom #peace #peaceofmind #metoo

text:
i did report. i was 9 and he was my mom's girlfriend's baby brother. his name is carlos alberto betancourt. #namethem

i was sleeping on the floor and he waited until everyone was asleep before he climbed in behind me under the covers and put his hand in my underwear. i was paralyzed with fear and pretended to be asleep in hopes he would stop digitally penetrating me, but he didn't. when morning was about to break he left. i told. i wasn't believed. 
ten years later, in colombia, my mom insisted i go out with him to the bar for a night of fun. instead of fun, he drugged and raped me in a tiny hotel room with his friends. on the way out they threw me down a flight of steep concrete stairs bc they couldn't carry me. i still have the permanent anal damage, and muscle dent from my right butt cheek impacting with the stairs over 20 years ago.  i didn't say a word. they hadn't believed me before. why bother now? my mom died thinking i didn't want to be with her. i just didn't want to be in the same house as my rapist. 
my freshman year in high school, i was picked up by a flirtatious high school senior from south dade high named john kyle. on our first date, he made me drink cisco and pulled out my tampon to rape me when i was too drunk to fight back. i told no one bc i wouldn't be believed.

after coming back from colombia, my new boyfriend michael smith would guilt me and demand sex until i lay there crying while he pumped away on top of me. i told no one bc i wouldn't be believed. 
#tellyourtruth #metoo #ibelieveher

hereâ€™s a pic of me looking thoughtful because i canâ€™t stop thinking about an incident that occurred thursday night. long story short: a new female friend and i couldnâ€™t shake a young local man who insisted on walking around with us even though we clearly did not want his attention. and when we announced we were going back to our hotel (because it was our only way to lose him, not that we said that) he turned negative and quickly started berating us. keep in mind the streets were dark and basically empty except for a few other men because of an impending storm. i was glad to not be alone.

i tell this story not to paint barbados in a bad light; everyone else has been incredibly friendly. but, in case you havenâ€™t noticed, women are angry this week. normally i would just brush this incident off â€“ as i have all other incidents of unwanted male attention while travelling. like the time a man sat down at my table at a restaurant in brussels and wouldnâ€™t leave even after i explicitly told him to do so. or the time a man in amsterdam grabbed my face and kissed me as i walked down the street. or the time a man in prague grabbed my ass by charles bridge.

i can handle that stuff but hereâ€™s the thing: i shouldnâ€™t have to. i shouldnâ€™t even be subjected to it in the first place. so, yeah, iâ€™m angry. and i donâ€™t know whether thatâ€™s a productive emotion but, for now, iâ€™m going to embrace it.

more thoughts on this later.

text:
how do you let go? 
iâ€™ve never regarded myself as an overprotective mother. sure, iâ€™m strict and  value strong morals and ethics, but helicopter-parenting has never had a draw. .
so this morning when my 11 year old asked if she could go â€œhang outâ€ with a friend for the day, my immediate response was: no. .
after long text conversations with the other parent, it dawned on me that it was my own experiences (sexual abuse in my own home as a child when left with older siblings and friends) and 2 date rape narrow escapes while at uni, which was driving my anxiety around letting my baby go...
.
sheâ€™s a mature, trustworthy, independent 11 year old who iâ€™m very proud of, but i also know that despite that, i can not control the actions of those around her, so the only things i can do is make sure she never gets into those situations herself. .
this morning i realised that even though i pray for her every day, iâ€™ve not let go. and that simply put means that i donâ€™t trust god to keep her safe... what???!!! .
so here i am, on my knees father, asking you for forgiveness for not trusting you when iâ€™ve asked you to take care of my precious girl. iâ€™ve asked and iâ€™ve not believed that you would give. .
thank you jesus for always pointing out the small areas in which we still need to let go and trust you more. thank you for healing those broken parts of me in the process thatâ€™s still broken yet hidden. 
letting go hurts but not letting go will hurt even more! i stand in awe of your goodness, your grace and your mercy. today and every day. ğŸ™ğŸ¼

text:
judy a worlds collide baby! a few years ago kizungu asked me to help him find the right wife.  i jokingly suggested the only women i knew, rachelâ€¦ she was the mother figure to all of our children in the congo.  they married and 2 years later judy arrived.  i was given the privilege to name her.  i chose the name of my recently departed mother in-law judith montgomery.  life is full of magic if you could only keep your heart open and your mind in the moment.  please take a breath today and honour those who have passed and those who have newly arrived. to the little girls who are innocent and to the women who have had no choice but to be strong in an environment where we as women are not treated and or considered equal to men. .
.
.
.
.
#women #strength #womencourage #shesaid #metoo #girlpower #womensupportwomen #womenempowerment

text:
stream of consciousness post. (also known as the "it's 4am and i cant fall back asleep" post).
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
lately, the focus of my classes have been breathing and moving through resistance. sending love to self and others. i have a tendency to get shut down and distract myself when resisting the uncomfortable feelings or thoughts, so i know how to linger in that resistance. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
this week has been insane in the news and i've asked my students to join me in setting the intention for peace to this great, stunning, warm, friendly, rich, poor, sad, divided, terrified country. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
cause man, i've been uncomfortable af. we're all in this together, no matter what side you're on. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
i don't pray. i've associated it with organized religion and have resisted any desire i have to do so, my whole life. but i have found myself praying. surrendering. asking for guidance and strength, cause that anger is getting me nowhere. â€¢

text:
let's talk about it
metoo activists claim that 90% of homicides are committed by male
the stat is 70% of homicides are committed by male and 30% by female
but
80% of the victims are male
and 20% are female
which means a female is more likely to kill a man than the other way round
yes it is completely immoral to ask for sexual favours in turn for opportunity
but isn't it immoral to provide sexual favours in order to get opportunity?
no means no! absolutely! make your kids learn this.
but how valid is the statement "i said yes because i didn't want to argue with my partner. it is still rape even though i said yes" or something like " 'okay then' doesn't mean you have my consent, it just meant you are forcing me. i am strong independent woman but i was afraid to say no so i said 'okay'"? what happened to "not guilty until proved criminal"? what about the cyber bullying of females who don't agree with the majority of feminist on the internet? 
what is the point of this?
girls, how dare he say you shouldn't him when he is talking? you are an independent woman and have every right to take part in the conversation and share your views. also, crack open his skull if he "attacks" your womanhood with his "mansplaining". kill him. it's alright. that will send a message. 
call out for the misogyny in the  society
filll your instagram stories with misandrist  memes. all in the name of humour. all in the name of equality.
if you are blessed with a daughter in the future
disown her if she doesn't agree with your views about feminism 
if you are cursed with a boy
change his sex
name him vagina
or even better
kill him
or tell him to kill himself because men are predetors
all in the name of social equality
i was going to write 
that you should raise your children with love, care and support. that you should teach them all the correct things. all this, irrespective of their gender. 
to teach them no means no and yes  means yes
to teach them to stand for themselves
to teach them to make their voices heard
to teach them to believe in themselves and not be afraid of their individuality
to teach them not to be ashamed of their own abilities
but don't bother.

text:
september's about to end and so is 2018. but looking back at these months, amidst several breakthroughs, the strongest ones have been #metoo & #timesup 
the world's (howsoever slow though) is surely moving towards radical development. with eventually every voice raised against wrongdoing and misogyny not just females, but the counterparts also stood up in support. 
time is really for up just about everything and everyone to keep mum behind those silhouettes of shame and fear. to come out in open, not as victims, but eventually as a fighter. 
easier said than done! the movement in my opinion, cannot be truly successful until the seed of fighting back is implanted in everyone's mind. not just the ones who suffer, but their related ones. recently padma lakshmi opened about how she was evidently sent back to her grandparents when she tried explaining her parents about her "incident". worse, the second time she was mistreated as a teenager, she suffered as a lack of awareness as to what exactly happened to her!
there are thousands of women, men, kids out there who are unaware about the fact that whatever is happening with them is inappropriate. and more so, kudos to our superficial society which is more bothered towards the "so-called" riti & riwaaz (rituals)!
what happens to those who are far away, from social media completely unaware of these movements... where girls are still married to men of their father or probably grandfather's age???
even if some fight back, what's the guarantee that they stay safe? who assures that, when we know we live in a world where boys lurk on bikes throwing acid out of mere revenge?
what happens to girls who are abused by their own relatives! to those who cannot speak/share not because they are weak. but because they've been taught to be quiet. more minds have been polluted to maintain "societal image" and until these are cleared of all this nonsense can peace be truly achieved. 
i am completely disturbed by the fact that a 10 point news app has 6 updates on the rape cases happening in a place, and 4 on the evolution around the globe. â€¢t h i n kâ€¢ â€¢ a c tâ€¢
#life #feminism #stop #enoughisenough #womenempowerment #unwomen #women #word

text_retweet:
i have been following the kavanaugh hearing closely over the past couple of days and i had no idea how strongly it would affect me.  i'm appalled by the reaction the dr ford has faced from some people - not just the name-calling and patronising behaviour that we have all seen, but also the death threats, email-hacking and even having to move out of the family home for safety.  i'm disgusted with a president whose initial sympathies on thursday were reportedly directed towards kavanaugh "for having to sit through" dr ford's testimony.  dr ford knew this is what she could face if she came forward, yet she still did, with nothing to gain from it, because it's her civic duty to do so.  this is a woman whose courage is unsurpassable, and it's really important that she testified in spite of all the negative vitorol she knew she would face.  her actions over the past few months have made a such a big impact on people across the world.  whatever the outcome may be, she is a hero for so many people and she's making history right now.â¤
.

text:
//
believe
her.
the thing that's fucking terrifying isn't that people don't believe survivors of rape and sexual assault. because, we all know womxn that have experienced it. and i don't mean one woman out of your group of loved ones, i mean it'd be surprising if any of them hadn't. so much so, that when a woman stands up and vocalises her trauma, it doesn't shock - we all know she's telling the truth. it's an every day occurrence - 'nothing remarkable happened'.
what is fucking terrifying is that even though they are believed - society (read : rich white men) do not care. they see it happening. they hear the recounts of trauma. they 100% know it happened. and they choose to ignore & continue anyway.
to everyone who's experienced anything like this, whether you weren't made to feel safe enough to be able tell your story, or if you did and were ignored anyway - i hear you, i believe you & i care.
.
.
.
.
.
#ionaharmony #believeher #believesurvivors #metoo #supportsurvivors #fuckthepatriarchy #stopkavanaugh #drford #feminism #feminist #bravery #christineblaseyford

text:
but saint laurent is operating like a nuclear reactor, and anthony vaccarelloâ€™s job is not to minimise the damages, rather to go head-to-head with slimane. his spring summer 2019 show was an unbelievable display of power. under the majesty of the eiffel tower were white californian palm trees (fake, thank god) and the water-drenched runway, which saw 95 modelâ€™s exits â€”slimaneâ€™s debut, three nights later, had 96. vaccarello can do sexy, itâ€™s always been at the core of his creative dna. the skimpy dress that will leave your grandparents outrÃ©: thatâ€™s what he does best. however the designer opened his show with a black suit, which is common sense. but unlike yves saint laurent, tailoring has never been his strongest point. it just doesnâ€™t look quite right and his attempt at modernising it fell flat. followed, almost 40 looks directly inspired by hedi slimaneâ€™s own saint laurent. why not? the brand has never sold as many dresses since its rebranding in 2012. though it is when he references monsieur saint laurent that vaccarello is at his strongest. some pieces were inspired by the 1972 stage costumes the house made for french singer sylvie vartan.  saint laurent proves that way, way before slimane, they were dressing rock chicks. elsewhere, see-through numbers ending the show brought to mind the autumn winter 1968 collection. revealing dresses were a tool for the emancipation of women during the sexual revolution, when women started to claim back their libido and bodies, just as they are today post-#metoo. still, vaccarello most of the time imagines a fantasised idea of sexiness, seen through a gay manâ€™s eyes. but there is always something chic about it, so itâ€™s up to women to get into it, or not.

text: we are living in a very transformative time for women. as i look back on my life, i can recall a number of situations where i was inappropriately touched or groped, subjected to disrespectful comments and i have one situation where i actually feared that i was going to be raped but fortunately i was not. i firmly believe that the conversations we are having now as a result of #metoo are permanently changing the landscape so that my daughter wonâ€™t have to go through some of the experiences i have had to go through and felt the need to keep quiet about. i am also glad that my son is growing up in a time where he clearly knows how to treat women as equals and with respect.  i had an interesting conversation with him last night about whether the rise of women had to mean the fall of men and we both agreed that it did not. we agreed that men and women can rise together and that both genders can benefit from the conversations that are happening as a result of the #metoo movement.  empowerment for one group does not have to mean disempowering another. there is room for all of us to live with respect and dignity. #empowerment #risetogether #transformation #equality #womensrights #feminism

text: gender should never come into play when it comes to bartending. women donâ€™t have anything superior to offer over men, in the same way men donâ€™t have anything to offer over women - but we should always be given the chance to outshine because we're just so good at what we do. individual genders/prejudices are not the subject of debate; we should have equality and inclusion across all fronts. the advice that i would look back and give to my 16 year old self, would be to seize every opportunity to work with people who value you for your skills and abilities, regardless of your gender. donâ€™t cower in the face of adversity, donâ€™t succumb to the status quo - always evolve, always grow, always do better. itâ€™ll be tough to rise above, but you have the power of voice, and command the room â€“ use the stage wisely, and while itâ€™ll take a long time to create an audience, once you do â€“ make sure you have something powerful to say. in our industry â€“ like many others that are public facing â€“ it takes a lifetime to build a positive reputation, and just seconds to destroy it. keep that in mind with each step, each interaction and each decision. bring those that have helped you along the way into the fold, and build a strong, powerful community that really creates impactful change â€“ everyone deserves a voice, but not everyone deserves an audience. dedicating this post to all the fighters out there today.

i have talked with those in my current community circle about the hearings and my own life as it relates to today, and i thought i was all talked out but here i am. 
what stirs me now as i finally lay down at the end of the day is how even though i, too, imagined i could move beyond my experiences... there they are fresh again where just yesterday they were pushed down and forgiven. clearly never forgotten. how could they be? how much of my life was influenced by those experiences? 
everything can be traced to a place where the far reaching tentacles of abuse come between me and my views, my perceptions, my choices.  i have worked hard to acknowledge and repair. i give credit to me for surviving. and most days i focus on the more pc and acceptable determination to â€˜be strongâ€™ and speak about it less as it was â€˜something from my past but i can be defined by my futureâ€™, as â€˜my future is up to meâ€™. but. seeing the courage be played out in public, hearing the impassioned pleas for justice, watching and reading the massive number of stories be posted, i am reminded. the sadness, the fear, the misunderstanding, the confusion, the death wish, the subsequent self abuse. i donâ€™t feel the need to relive the details or situation, but i find it impossible to ignore the emotions come back to visit like out of a grave unearthed. i feel them now and am pained for everyone it turns had to go through anything similar. i want to appreciate my/our feelings in a new way - a way that empowers me to be louder! vigilant for those without a clear voice of their own. for everyone who plays their part in this, i thank you. 
i believe. 
i believe myself. 
i believe her.
we are one in the same and we all deserve much better.

text:
when it comes to the #metoo conversations i'm sad to hear these 4 things: 
1) why do you speak up now so many years later? 
2) it's a manhunt. 
3) where is the #metoomovement for men? why is it only about women?
4) how am i supposed to know how to behave now since everything is offensive?

let's recap people! 
1) being harrased or abused is fucking traumatic. 
trauma itself causes the brain to shut down some functions and focus only in survival. this phase can last for years and years..(read about trauma if you want to know more.)
also coming out means you lose your privacy.
people may not believe you and that causes more pain & suffering.
you're motives are questioned time and again. 
fear of professional consequenses on top of personal are huge.
the ones who were being harrased also blame themselves for what happened. 
it takes time and courage to come out and be heard. 
2) it's not. 
it's humanbeings trying to right the wrongs.
if you happen to be a male that is accused of something then you are a male being accused.
no hunt nor manhunt there. 
3) yup! i hope everybody would speak up about injustice they have faced.
manners & safety apply to everyone!

4) very simple: everything is not offensive. only offensive behaviour is! 
so don't do that ğŸ˜Š 
if you don't know the difference between drinking and boofing (sike! check out kavanaugh & yearbook) i mean good and not good behaviour you can i.e ask someone for an opinion or advice. 
ask, listen, talk, think...there are many ways to get information. 
read about the subject, follow the public conversations, google it, do something...
please don't turn into passive or agressive.

peace and no motherfuckers ğŸ¤Ÿ

text:
some female folks saw me tonight and told me they appreciated the fierce feminist witchy vibes that i was giving off in my mood and my outfit. it wasn't what i was intentionally going for but i'll take it. i look tired in this shot because i am tired. the kind of bone tired that comes along with fighting for what's right and battling ptsd and supporting fellow survivors and educating those who don't understand and creating art and remaining hopeful in the face of it all. i am here tonight sending love and healing and fellowship and sisterhood and hope out into the world right now. we all need it.
.
.
. .
.
.
#believesurvivors #metoo #hope #feminist #womensupportingwomen #survivor #survivorssupportingsurvivors

text:
the ongoing brett kavanaugh saga looks far from a resolution. much less one that would see a peaceful consensus.Â 
when republican senators brought in experienced sex crimes prosecutor rachel mitchell, skepticism abounded. she was touted as being an outsider in the affair. a neutral whoâ€™d get the job done and dig deep for the truth.Â at least thatâ€™s what @gop spokespeople said as she geared up for questioning.
amidst the flurry of misconduct allegations thrown in kavanaughâ€™s direction, itâ€™s important for both sides to get to the bottom of whatâ€™s happening. 
the candidate and his fellow party members claim itâ€™s a classic case of political smearing. a decades-long vendetta for his role in mounting a case against @bill_.clinton in the 90s.â€¨@thedemocrats consider it yet another example of corruption and abuse of power. perpetrated not-so-coincidentally by a @realdonaldtrump sympathizer and nominee.
the woman in the eye of the storm is christine blasey ford, a professor at @paloaltou. sheâ€™s made startling revelations about an incident that happened nearly 40 years ago. kavanaugh and a friend lured her into a room, where things took a turn for the worse. fortunately, if you can call it that, kavanaugh wasnâ€™t able to complete the assault.Â 
not that that makes it much less terrible. 
a particularly messy line of questioning cut through fordâ€™s admitted fear of flying. mitchell asked ford how she got to dc if she was so afraid of flying. and whether sheâ€™d flown in the past.Â 
in a few words, it was a pretty nonsensical and nit-picky attempt to put fordâ€™s credibility into doubt.
trustworthy leadership is impossible without a clearly communicated goal. to get anything done, leaders need to get this right. they have to be honest with themselves and others.
picking mitchell seemed less like a move to get to the truth and more a chance to put her down. leaders are constantly judged by their actions and words. in such a delicate case, several reputations are at stake.
and trust is a wall built one brick at a time.
#leadership #kavanaugh #politics #metoo #movement #washingtondc #ford #gop #reputation #trust #truth #nimbus

text:
was i brave for dropping everything on a decision to come to a foreign speaking country? or was i completely ignorant? or was i crazy? no. 
i had lived abroad for a year in asia before.
and i had lived abroad in america for 8 years. america really was the slow death of me. i foresaw income was not sustainable. and i was mired in helpless people around me who could not support themselves. people who work gigs are the main workforce in la. this is not a sustainable model for a high cost of living country. one gap, one injury, one sickness and youâ€™re either bankrupt or injured for life unable to recover. 
to me, moving to a completely new model of income was a no-brainer. i already know the opportunities and struggles of american gig-workers. now i simply had to get boots on the ground and feel security again.
but this journey is still mired in peeling myself away from america and all that it burdened me with. mentally, monetarily, and sexually. 
the americaâ€™s way of forcing people to scrap for work, has burdened women with men who are untrusted and canâ€™t close deals for themselves. 
women are a specialized bedrock for guys to do business with. just because they want to see us in the room. they have befallen themselves with so little to be trusted as a race, that single men at a certain pinnacle of his expected career is dead in the water, without a female trust ambassador. 
and this is where i feel the main movement against women is happening. itâ€™s really the unsustainable gig work growth thatâ€™s forcing a polarized look at men vs women. 
when i look for people i relate to now - at the same career phase as myself, i am suspicious of talking with guys. i preferably only want to relate to women.
we know what it is to work hard when we want that career. for men, this is a completely different experience. and now shock reality has hit them, many are realizing the gender equity of a work force must close the gap. but there are some guys who are very bitter about it and make the laws and rules to fuck women over intentionally.
i literally see myself as having jumped ship from america back to europe. it was good while it lasted, but that country does not deserve me.

text:
hello, anxiety, thanks for not letting me sleep. this kavanaugh situation has me filled with more emotions than iâ€™m able to contain. actually, iâ€™m back to having nightmares and screaming in my sleep. i donâ€™t realize iâ€™m doing this until iâ€™m in my hallway, trying to catch my breath and have to remind myself iâ€™m okay, and iâ€™m safe. then, i go back to bed but always locking my bedroom door â€œjust in case.â€ how anyone can back this man is pure insanity. this is so much more than being a republican or a democrat. if you do support him, please unfriend me now. youâ€™re basically giving me a huge middle finger, and i donâ€™t want you in my life. if you choose to label me as unstable or insane, iâ€™d love for you to walk a mile in my shoes. actually, the first 18 yrs of my life as i fought off a belligerent,alcoholic father who beat me and tortured my mother in front of me. iâ€™m often surprised iâ€™m still alive. the number of times i was hit repeatedly in the back of my head (my cervical spine as seen on x-rays changed from that trauma) or had a gun pointed at me in our living room while he was in a blackout telling me he would kill us, still echos in my mind. 
you want to know why we didnâ€™t report? because it would embarrass him, he had a violent childhood, and i needed to be more sympathetic to his mental health. no concern for me as a developing young woman or my mother who was in pure survival mode. i didnâ€™t deserve this. no one deserves this. however, this was my reality, and iâ€™m in a daily battle for survival over my damaged mind. a damaged mind i did not ask for. #stopkavanaugh #metoo #cptsd #abusesurvivor #mentalhealth #ptsdsurvivor #fear #sadness #trauma

text:
holding on 
to everything i thought
i let go of
dismissing the emotion
refusing it
a moment of grief
didnâ€™t realize i had built
a collection with it
pain
all different shades and shapes
every time it arises
triggered
i react in typical self defense
walls up 
guardians of this emotional galaxy
poised to destroy any threat
to the current balance of power
calm and steady cannot survive
the toll that healing takes
the time
the patience
the focus and strength
all so necessary
just out of my reach
- @stacieseidlwrites #metoo #believewomen #thankyoudrford

"hanging shoes"

i don't want to post texts like this, when i'm talking about my experiences of inc*st and the traumatic neglecting i got put through. but at the same time i really want to. i want to combine my photos, which i am really proud of, with my childhood.
it's really tough, but bear with me, i'm gonna make it.
